  title_alias = 'The Sufficient; Al Kafi; El-Kafi; Alkafi; Al-Kāfī; Kitab al-Kafi; The Sufficient Hadith Collection; Kafi; Usul al-Kafi; Furu al-Kafi; Rawdat al-Kafi; The Four Books; Shia Hadith Collection',
  keywords = '{"Al-Kafi", "Kitab al-Kafi", "Muhammad ibn Yaqub al-Kulayni", "al-Kulayni", "Kulayni", "Hadith collection", "Shia hadith", "Twelver Shia", "Imami hadith", "Four Books", "Kutub Arba", "Usul al-Kafi", "Furu al-Kafi", "Rawdat al-Kafi", "The Sufficient", "Hadith compilation", "Prophetic traditions", "Imamic traditions", "Ahl al-Bayt", "Islamic jurisprudence", "Fiqh", "Theology", "Usul al-Din", "Isnad", "Chain of transmission", "Sahih", "Hasan", "Muwathaq", "Qawi", "Daif", "Hadith classification", "Islamic epistemology", "Aql", "Reason", "Ilm", "Knowledge", "Tawhid", "Divine unity", "Hujja", "Divine proof", "Imamate", "Wilayah", "Guardianship", "Tahara", "Ritual purity", "Salat", "Prayer", "Zakat", "Obligatory charity", "Sawm", "Fasting", "Hajj", "Pilgrimage", "Jihad", "Nikah", "Marriage", "Talaq", "Divorce", "Islamic law", "Sharia", "Rey", "4th century AH", "10th century CE", "Classical period", "400 hadith booklets", "Usul arba mia", "Quranic verification", "Book of God"}',
  description = 'In "Al-Kafi," Muhammad ibn Yaqub al-Kulayni analyzes the foundational hadith corpus of Twelver Shia Islam through comprehensive preservation and systematization. Al-Kulayni systematically argues that this collection represents a "sufficient" (*kafi*) repository of all necessary religious knowledge, demonstrating this through an encyclopedic methodology compiled over twenty years from the Four Hundred Hadith Booklets (*Usul arba''a mi''a*). This thesis is built upon three foundational pillars: *Usul al-Kafi* (theological foundations and epistemology), *Furu'' al-Kafi* (practical jurisprudence), and *Rawdat al-Kafi* (miscellaneous traditions and Imamic letters). The work grounds its authenticity in rigorous *isnad* (chain of transmission) verification and Quranic concordance principles, systematically organizing 16,199 narrations across theological, jurisprudential, and ethical domains. Al-Kulayni''s comprehensive approach transforms this work into the foundational hadith collection of Twelver Shia Islam, offering an authoritative framework for Islamic scholarship that encompasses divine unity (*tawhid*), Imamic authority (*wilayah*), and practical guidance for Muslim life.'
